Sir James Dalrymple tells us that he will not be at the pains to compare the Oxford edition with the manuscript copies to be found in Scotland or England‚ but that he will content him- self with the printed one.†

Nicolson, in his Scottish Historical Library, had done much to perpetuate this belief, and has in other respects clouded the subject by the unguarded, erroneOUS, and contradictory manner in which he speaks of our Chronicle. The authority which is gen- erally attached to his work, somewhat undeservedly, renders it necessary to examine his statementS, without reverting to those advanced by Mackenzie and Dalrymple, which he incorporates with his own.
